The better world is already here
COPENHAGEN – For centuries, optimists and pessimists have debated the condition of the world.
Pessimists see a world in which more people mean less food, in which increasing resource demand leads to overexploitation and war, and in which the growing production capacity of the last decades leads to more pollution and global warming.
One of the holy texts of the current generation of pessimists, The Limits to Growth, still influences the environmental movement today.
Optimists, on the other hand, claim that everything will get better – human health, standard of living, environmental quality, and so on.
From their opponents, they are seen as "economists of abundance" who trust the market, supposedly solving all problems.
But instead of picking facts and stories that fit into a grand narrative of decline or progress, we should try to compare all areas of human existence to see whether the world is really getting better or worse.
Exactly this is what I have tried to achieve together with 21 leading economists worldwide by developing a ranking list of the last 150 years.
In ten areas – including health, education, war, gender relations, air pollution, climate change, and biodiversity – the economists answered the same question: How high were the relative costs of this problem in each year from 1900 to 2013, including forecasts up to 2050.
Using classical economic assessments of all factors from deaths, health damages, and illiteracy to the destruction of wetlands and higher hurricane risk due to global warming, the economists detail the cost of each individual problem.
To estimate the magnitude of the problem, it is compared to the total resources available for its solution.
This makes the size of the problem clear as a share of GDP.
And the trends since 1900 are partly surprising.
Let's look at gender inequality.
Back then, we essentially excluded almost half of the world's population from production.
In 1900, only 15% of the world's workforce was female.
What are the losses that arose from this low percentage?
Even when we take into account the higher costs of educating women, and that someone must do the unpaid housework, the losses amounted to at least 17% of the world's GDP in 1900.
Today, with a higher female participation rate and smaller income differences, the loss is 7% – and is likely to fall to 4% by 2050.
It will probably be surprising that climate change from 1900 to 2025 is expected to bring a growing net benefit – rising up to 1.5% of GDP per year.
This is due to the different effects of global warming. When it is only moderate, the benefits outweigh the costs.
On the one hand, the higher CO2 emissions were a blessing for agriculture, as the gas acts as fertilizer. This is the largest positive effect, amounting to 0.8% of GDP.
Similarly, a moderate warming prevents more deaths from cold than it causes additional deaths from heat.
It also reduces heating demand more than it creates new cooling demand, which corresponds to a benefit of about 0.4% of GDP.
On the other hand, warming leads to water scarcity, which costs about 0.2% of GDP, and has a negative impact on ecosystems such as wetlands, which corresponds to a loss of about 0.1%.
However, with further rising temperatures, the costs increase and the benefits decrease, dramatically reducing the net benefit.
After 2070, global warming will cause net costs to the world, which justifies cost-efficient climate protection today and in the coming decades.
However, the ranking list also shows us that the world's largest environmental problem is indoor air pollution, which puts things into the right perspective.
Today, more than three million people die each year from indoor air pollution caused by harmful emissions from cooking and heating, which corresponds to a loss of 3% of global GDP.
But in 1900, these costs corresponded to 19% of GDP, and it is expected that they will decline to 1% by 2050.
Health indicators have improved the most worldwide.
Until the late 18th century, human life expectancy had barely changed.
The size of the gain since 1900 cannot be overstated: At that time, the world's life expectancy was 32 years, and today it is 69 years (and probably 76 years by 2050).
The main influencing factor was the decline in infant mortality.
For example, as late as 1970, only 5% of infants were vaccinated against measles, tetanus, whooping cough, diphtheria, and polio.
In the year 2000, it was 85%, which led to the saving of three million lives every year – more than would have been saved by world peace throughout the entire 20th century.
This success has many parents.
The Gates Foundation and the GAVI Alliance have spent more than 2.5 billion USD on vaccines and promised a further 10 billion.
Through efforts by the Rotary Club, the World Health Organization, and many others, cases of polio have been reduced by 99% since 1979.
In economic terms, the costs of poor health at the beginning of the 20th century amounted to astonishing 32% of global GDP.
Today they have decreased to about 11% and are expected to halve again by 2050.
Even though the optimists are not right in all points (the loss of biodiversity in the twentieth century probably costs about 1% of GDP annually, and at some places significantly more), the overall picture is clear.
Most of the examined topics show improvements of 5-20% of GDP.
And the general trend is even clearer.
Relative to the resources available for their solution, global problems have dramatically decreased.
Naturally, this does not mean that there are no more problems.
Even though they have become smaller in the areas of health, education, malnutrition, air pollution, gender inequality, and trade, they are still large.
But realists should slowly get used to the idea that the world has improved greatly.
Furthermore, the ranking list shows us where the challenges for a better 2050 lie.
We should not orient our view of the future towards the most horrifying stories or the loudest interest groups, but towards objective assessments of where we can achieve the greatest improvements.
